defaultOur Committee, on behalf of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in Ireland, confined its 
defaultexamination
default of the provisions of this Bill to Schedule 5, Insolvency and Company Law.  Our 
defaultspecific
default comments on those provisions are attached herewith.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe respond to a number of the general questions posed in the Call for Written Evidence as 
defaultfollows
default:
default&#xa0;
defaultQ. 3default              defaultAre the changes proposed in the draft Bill evidence-based and have any risks associated with the changes been taken adequately into account?
default&#xa0;
defaultA. 3default              
defaultWe are not convinced of the benefits/risk balance in the proposal to remove the obligation on a bankrupt to present a statement of affairs when the petition is presented by a creditor.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ. 4default              
defaultDoes the draft Bill achieve its purpose of reducing the regulatory burden on business, organisations and individuals effectively and fairly?
default&#xa0;
defaultA. 4default              
defaultOn balance
default, yes.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQ. 5default              
defaultWill the draft Bill generally benefit businesses by offsetting other regulatory burdens?
default&#xa0;
defaultA. 5default              
defaultReduction in administrative burdens in insolvency assignments will reduce costs. Consequently, more funds will be available for the creditors of the insolvent business.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ. 6default    To what extent does the draft Bill benefit consumers as well as businesses?
default&#xa0;
defaultA. 6 default   Amendments within Schedule 5 may benefit consumers who are creditors of insolvent
default           
defaultbusinesses
default.
